<HEAD>Scientists Agree to be Patient in Search for Life on Mars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists searching for life on <ORGANIZATION>Mars</ORGANIZATION>
agreed <DATE>Saturday</DATE> that they must be patient and focus on learning
more about the environment of the cold, dry planet.
   ``If we're going to find life on Mars, it's not going to be just
sitting around in the dust someplace,'' said <PERSON>John D. Rummel</PERSON>, who
directs life biology research for the <ORGANIZATION>National Aeronautics and
Space Administration</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``We're going to have to find places on Mars that are more
likely to contain life forms than you would find at random,'' he
said.
   <PERSON>Rummel</PERSON> was among two dozen scientists from <LOCATION>North America</LOCATION>, the
<LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> who attended the International
Symposium on the <ORGANIZATION>Biological Exploration of Mars</ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION>Florida State
University</ORGANIZATION>.
   Three speakers cautioned that it was too soon to conduct direct
life experiments on Mars, but <PERSON>Rummel</PERSON> said most of the scientists
agreed the planet should be studied for insights that could lead to
a discovery of life on the planet.
   ``Mars is not considered by many people to be a lifeless
planet,'' <PERSON>Rummel</PERSON> said.
   Ten years ago, the landings on Mars during the Viking missions
detected no signs of life on <ORGANIZATION>Mars</ORGANIZATION>, the most Earth-like planet in
the solar system.
   Scientists believe the planet was once more hospitable for the
evolution of life than it is now. Conditions grew harsher,
primarily drier and colder.
   <PERSON>Rummel</PERSON> said some scientists believe that signs of life, either
past or present, might be discovered deeper under the surface, near
heat sources where water might be found.
   The latest data from Mars came from unmanned Soviet missions in
<DATE>1988</DATE>. The <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> plans to send a spacecraft to orbit Mars in
<DATE>1992</DATE> and the Soviets plan a <DATE>1994</DATE> mission that would land an
unmanned robotic rover vehicle and balloons to explore the planet's
surface.
   On Earth, scientists are studying volcanoes, ocean bottoms,
lakes and rocks in <LOCATION>Antarctica</LOCATION> and Siberian permafrost to see what
kinds of life can survive under Martian-like conditions.
   E. <PERSON>Imre Friedmann</PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION>Florida State</ORGANIZATION> researcher who organized the
meeting, said there's a good likelihood that life once existed on
Mars.
   ``You cannot really express it numerically, you cannot quantify
it, but it is certainly good enough to justify serious effort to
verify whether or not this is really the case,'' <PERSON>Friedmann</PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
