<LEADPARA>  The United States could land people on Mars 10 years sooner for about
one-tenth of the estimated cost by teaming up with the Soviet Union and
scuttling the space station that NASA has planned, says a group of Stanford
University professors.;    They said their proposal could save up to $480
billion from the National Aeronautics and Space Administration's estimated
$540 billion price tag over the next few decades.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  STANFORD TEAM SETS SIGHTS ON MARS
URGES U.S.-SOVIET EFFORT TO CUT COSTS, HASTEN
FLIGHT  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Additional information attached to the end of this article  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The <ORGANIZATION>Stanford</ORGANIZATION> plan was scheduled to be presented today to the <ORGANIZATION>National Space
Council</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>D.C.</LOCATION>, which advises the president on space policy.;   
Although the idea of a joint U.S.-Soviet mission to <ORGANIZATION>Mars</ORGANIZATION> was proposed several
years ago by President <PERSON>Gorbachev</PERSON>, planning for the effort never got under way
and each country has been pursuing its own scheme.;    The American version,
endorsed by President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> two years ago, includes building a space station
and a lunar base before going to <ORGANIZATION>Mars</ORGANIZATION>, at a total cost of up to <MONEY>$540 billion.</MONEY>;
   The cost of the space station plan has been the focus of intense debate in
<ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> voted earlier this month to keep funding alive for another
year, rejecting an earlier vote by the appropriations committee to scuttle the
project.;    Thousands of jobs in <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> and elsewhere hinge on the <MONEY>$30
billion</MONEY> space station plan. <ORGANIZATION>Lockheed Missiles &amp; Space Co.</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Sunnyvale</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Silicon Valley</LOCATION>'s largest employer, has estimated it would lose <MONEY>$1 billion</MONEY> in
space-station-related contracts over the next decade if the plan is scuttled.;
   Critics of the space station plan, however, contend it would rob funds from
other space programs and from social programs for the poor.;    The <ORGANIZATION>Stanford</ORGANIZATION>
plan bypasses both the space station and the moon base in favor of going to
Mars directly.;    Sometime around the year <DATE>2012</DATE>, a series of spacecraft
carrying cargo and crew would be boosted into low Earth orbit aboard the
Soviet Energia rocket, which can carry much heavier loads than anything <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>
now has to offer.;    They then would be flung out of orbit like rocks from a
sling for the nine-month journey to Mars.;    When the crew of three men and
three women arrived, they would find apartments and a garage with tracked
exploration vehicles waiting for them, sent up in advance by an unmanned
rocket. They would stay about a year before embarking for the nine-month
journey back.;    The total cost: <MONEY>$60 billion</MONEY>, including several preliminary
unmanned missions to map the Martian surface and explore it with robots.;   
Scrapping the space station -- now estimated to cost up to <MONEY>$120 billion</MONEY> over
its lifetime -- and a <MONEY>$10 billion</MONEY> heavy-lift rocket would save money and more
than 10 years.;    The no-frills mission would also take two steps to protect
the health of the astronauts during their long flight. It would incorporate 22
tons of water and other shielding into the spacecraft to insulate them from
cosmic radiation, which could reach a lethal peak during solar storms.;    And
the craft would rotate four times per minute to provide some artificial
gravity in the hope of avoiding deterioration of the astronauts' hearts, bones
and blood vessels.;    The plan was drafted by graduate students in a <ORGANIZATION>Stanford</ORGANIZATION>
space systems engineering class taught by <PERSON>Bruce Lusignan</PERSON>, professor of
electrical engineering. The <ORGANIZATION>Stanford</ORGANIZATION> team also included a former vice
president of <ORGANIZATION>TRW</ORGANIZATION>'s spacecraft engineering division, <PERSON>Emery Reeves</PERSON>; an expert in
robotics, <PERSON>Thomas Binford</PERSON>; and <PERSON>Larry Colin</PERSON>, former chief of the space science
division at NASA/Ames.;    Although it was done as an educational exercise,
<PERSON>Lusignan</PERSON> is scheduled to present it to the <ORGANIZATION>Space Council</ORGANIZATION> at the urging of
scientists who reviewed it.;    <PERSON>Roy Merrill</PERSON>, a <PERSON>Lawrence Livermore</PERSON> software
engineer specializing in robotics who reviewed parts of the plan, said it was
based on conservative, tested technology. "It's definitely a viable way to
tackle the problem," he said.;    <PERSON>Colin</PERSON> said some people are hoping the
<ORGANIZATION>Stanford</ORGANIZATION> plan could push <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> into taking a mission to Mars more seriously. He
added, "You don't need a space station. You don't need a lunar program. You
can just go to Mars.";    The study was partly funded by <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Ames Research
Center.</ORGANIZATION>;  <ORGANIZATION>Stanford</ORGANIZATION> team; The Mars exploration plan was drafted by graduate
students in a <ORGANIZATION>Stanford</ORGANIZATION> space systems engineering class, assisted by:;
(box)<PERSON>Bruce Lusignan</PERSON>, professor of electrical engineering; (box)<PERSON>Emery Reeves</PERSON>, a
former vice president of <ORGANIZATION>TRW</ORGANIZATION>'s spacecraft engineering division; (box)<PERSON>Thomas
Binford</PERSON>, an expert in robotics; (box)<PERSON>Larry Colin</PERSON>, former chief of the space
science division at NASA/Ames  </TEXT>
