<HEAD>Council Says U.S. Should Explore Use of Nuclear Power in Space</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Space explorers will have to use nuclear power
on Mars, and the <ORGANIZATION>National Science Council</ORGANIZATION> says the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>
should study employing nuclear rockets to get travelers to the
planet.
   In a <DATE>Friday</DATE> report to Vice President <PERSON>Dan Quayle</PERSON>, the council
acknowledged ``formidable barriers of public acceptance'' to the
use of nuclear power in space.
   However, it said the use of such power ``eventually will be
essential'' on both the <PERSON>Moon</PERSON> and Mars because of heavy energy
demands.
   It also recommended testing and possibly a demonstration in
space of the feasibility of sending rockets to Mars by nuclear
propulsion.
   The report analyzed a study done by the <ORGANIZATION>National Aeronautics and
Space Administration</ORGANIZATION> as part of President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON>'s initiative to put
bases on the <PERSON>Moon</PERSON> and Mars early in the next century.
   Among its findings:
   _<ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> needs to study the effects of long-term space flight on
human beings because on the basis of present knowledge ``a
multiyear exposure to weightlessness, even with on-board exercise
and countermeasures and an intermediate stay on the surface of
Mars, presents unacceptable risks to the crew.''
   _Operation of a <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> space station by the <DATE>late 1990s</DATE> as
scheduled is a ``reasonable assumption,'' but plans for the station
are not adequate for a Moon-Mars mission. The station ``may not be
the most appropriate staging base for the <PERSON>Moon</PERSON> and Mars'' and it is
possible that ``an additional station ... will eventually become
necessary.''
   _Although the <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> proposals envision bases on <ORGANIZATION>Mars</ORGANIZATION>, ``it
appears that a station in Mars orbit requires a less demanding
infrastructure than a surface base and might serve a useful purpose
in the early stages of human space exploration.''
   _Possibilities for international cooperation should be explored
because breakthroughs have been made in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> and elsewhere
and ``most importantly, the <ORGANIZATION>USSR</ORGANIZATION> has substantial relevant
capability, demonstrated continued interest in Mars, and an
apparent strong desire for cooperation with the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> in Mars
exploration.''
   The council's study, made by a 14-member committee named in
<DATE>January</DATE>, said nuclear rockets would reach Mars in one-half to
one-third the time needed for single-stage chemical propulsion
systems. Unmanned spacecraft have made the 111 million mile voyage
to <ORGANIZATION>Mars</ORGANIZATION> in six months.
   ``The use of nuclear technology in space faces formidable
barriers of public acceptance, however, especially if employed in
<LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> orbit,'' the council said. ``Therefore, issues of safety are
paramount in research and development.''
   It said one type of nuclear technology, known as the NERVA
class, ``is available for full-scale development'' and ``should be
evaluated for injection to Mars in competition with hydrogen-oxygen
chemical systems.''
   ``If careful systems studies ... show a significant advantage
for nuclear rockets in trip time or in weight to orbit, an in-space
demonstration of this technology should be done as soon as
possible,'' the council said.
   ``It will not be feasible to select the nuclear rocket as a
baseline in a system architecture until such a demonstration has
been conducted.''
   After announcing the <ORGANIZATION>Moon-Mars</ORGANIZATION> initiative <DATE>July 20</DATE>, the <DATE>20th
anniversary</DATE> of the first Moon landing, <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> asked <PERSON>Quayle</PERSON>, chairman
of the <ORGANIZATION>National Space Council</ORGANIZATION>, to explore ways of carrying it out.
   <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> made a 90-day study, and <PERSON>Quayle</PERSON> asked the <ORGANIZATION>National Research
Council</ORGANIZATION>, an arm of the congressionally chartered <ORGANIZATION>National Academy
of Sciences</ORGANIZATION>, to evaluate it.
</TEXT>
