<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   Debate Over Space Policy May Produce Program
   That Delays Plans, Wastes Funds, Pleases No One
   ----
   By Bob Davis
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/21/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<MS>
TECHNOLOGY (TEC)
</MS>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<RE>
NORTH AMERICA (NME)
UNITED STATES (US)
</RE>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The current fight over the future of U.S.
space exploration may eventually yield a program that sets
the nation firmly on the course of a permanent presence in
space -- or a program that delays projects, wastes money and
in the end satisfies no one.
   At the heart of the controversy is the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration's plan to build by the
end of the decade a $30 billion orbital space station manned
by four astronauts. The space station is central to the
administration's broader aim of using astronauts to explore
the solar system -- a goal that divides Congress and dismays
space scientists backing a variety of unmanned space --
science projects.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   True believers dominate the debate. Space exploration
requires "a leap of faith, above and beyond analysis," says
<PERSON>Richard Darman</PERSON>, the powerful <ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION> budget director who
says he has believed since childhood that humans will someday
live on other planets. "Almost by personality type, you want
to press limits, press frontiers, or you don't."
   But many space scientists say manned expeditions are more
folly than frontier. Much of the effort in manned programs
goes into protecting astronauts from space hazards rather
than pushing the limits of technology, says <PERSON>Eugene Levy</PERSON>, head
of the <ORGANIZATION>University of Arizona</ORGANIZATION>'s planetary program. He says
that sending unmanned spacecraft to Mars would cost far less
than the space station, and would do much more to advance
research in computers, robotics and communications.
   "These are the critical technologies in which <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> is
eating our lunch," he says.
   Scientists have been battling manned projects, without
much luck, since the beginning of the Space Age; President
<PERSON>Kennedy</PERSON> rejected the advice of his science adviser when he
decided to land a man on the moon. But the influence of
scientists has been growing steadily as first the space
shuttle, then the space station, ran into trouble from
spiraling costs and design flaws.
   Last <DATE>December</DATE>, a <ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION> panel ranked unmanned
projects ahead of manned exploration as a goal for the space
program. Then, last month, an influential <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION>
appropriations subcommittee voted to kill the space station
while preserving big increases for other forms of space
science. Space scientists were elated; <PERSON>James Van Allen</PERSON>, the
famed <ORGANIZATION>University of Iowa</ORGANIZATION> physicist who discovered the
radiation belts that ring the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>, speaks for many of his
colleagues when he calls the station "a monster that will
kill off a lot of space science." Physicists, geologists,
chemists and astronomers all lobbied against the space
station.
   But during a <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> vote on the station earlier this month,
lawmakers who had ignored the space program for years rose to
defend not only the station but manned space expeditions,
too. Many of the lawmakers had been lobbied fiercely by the
<ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION> and aerospace contractors; some also had <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>
centers or aerospace firms in their states. But the fervor of
their rhetoric indicated that they were moved as much by the
romance of space exploration -- and the memories of the
Apollo moon landings -- as by pork-barrel politics.
   "We are the first nation to effectively move into outer
space," said Republican Rep. <PERSON>Don Ritter</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Pennsylvania</LOCATION>, a
former engineering-school professor who supports the station.
"It is the pinnacle of <LOCATION>America</LOCATION>'s national achievement." Added
<LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> Democrat <PERSON>Jack Brooks</PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION>Judiciary Committee</ORGANIZATION> chairman,
whose district includes the Johnson Space Center: "The future
of the universe is in space."
   The <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> finally voted 240-173 to build the station, but
at the cost of freezing all <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> projects at their current
levels. The biggest loser was space science, which had been
slated to receive big increases for an X-ray space telescope,
two unmanned spacecraft to explore <ORGANIZATION>Saturn</ORGANIZATION> and a comet, and a
satellite project to study the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s climate.
   The vote didn't resolve the dispute over space priorities;
it just made the battle more bitter. The <ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>
promise they will lobby to restore science funds in the
<ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION>. But the comet mission will probably be canceled,
congressional and <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> officials say, and the others face
substantial cutbacks and delays before they reach the launch
pad. The agency's plans to build an infrared space telescope
and launch an unmanned probe to the sun are also in limbo.
"If we get pushed hard enough, we'll have to reassess all the
{science} programs," says <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> chief <ORGANIZATION>Richard Truly</ORGANIZATION>.
   <PERSON>John Bahcall</PERSON>, an astrophysicist at the <ORGANIZATION>Institute for
Advanced Study</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Princeton</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.J.</LOCATION>, who organized opposition
to the station, says he's bewildered by <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>'s willingness to
sacrifice science projects. "If <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> were a mental patient
instead of an agency, you'd say it has schizophrenia," he
says. <PERSON>Mr. Darman</PERSON>, the budget director, contends that station
opponents want to protect their research grants, not help the
space program. "They're not engaged in big-think," he says.
   <PERSON>Alex Roland</PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION>Duke University</ORGANIZATION> space historian, says he
sees a disturbing parallel between the current battle and the
<DATE>one a decade ago</DATE> over the space shuttle. Then, <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> slashed
spending for a series of science missions to conserve funds
for the shuttle. Between mid-1978 and mid-1989, for instance,
the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> didn't launch a single planetary probe. With
continuing budget constraints, <PERSON>Mr. Roland</PERSON> says <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> will be
forced to make similar sacrifices to build the station. He
calls the space station "the son of shuttle."
   This time, though, not only science will lose, but
exploration too, warns <LOCATION>Michigan</LOCATION> Democratic Rep. <PERSON>Robert
Traxler</PERSON>, who heads the appropriations panel that tried and
failed to kill the station. Indeed, so far, <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> has
shown no willingness to fund the expensive propulsion
technologies that the administration says are crucial if
astronauts are ever to go beyond the station and off to Mars.
Rep. <PERSON>Traxler</PERSON> calls the administration's exploration plans "an
enormously expensive fantasy which will have severe adverse
effects on domestic programs."
   Not at all, says <PERSON>Mr. Darman</PERSON>. He insists the administration
is committed to preventing the station from cannibalizing the
rest of the space program; one idea being explored is the
creation of a space trust fund, modeled on the interstate
highway trust fund, to pay for construction in space.
("There's no funding source, so it's not a viable idea yet,"
the budget director concedes.)
   Mostly, though, <PERSON>Mr. Darman</PERSON> counsels faith. The space
station is just the first small step in manned exploration of
the solar system, he says. Station astronauts will explore
the effects of weightlessness on materials, themselves and
other living organisms. After that, other uses for the space
station will emerge -- and with them an even broader
political constituency for manned exploration. "People's
earthly interests will grow and grow," he prophesies.
</TEXT>
