<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ground Control Error Leaves Soviet Mars Probe Worthless</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with space official saying mistake has
made Mars probe worthless. DELETES outdated material. ADDS byline.
No pickup.
^By ANDREW KATELL</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet space official said <DATE>today</DATE> that a ground
control operator sent an incorrect message to a Soviet space probe
bound for Mars, and the unmanned spacecraft is now worthless.
   ``Only a miracle can save it,'' <PERSON>Roald Z. Sagdeyev</PERSON>, head of the
<ORGANIZATION>Soviet Space Research Institute</ORGANIZATION>, said in an interview with <ORGANIZATION>The
Associated Press</ORGANIZATION>.
   Earlier, the official <ORGANIZATION>Tass</ORGANIZATION> news agency announced that ground
control had lost communications contact with the Phobos 1 probe,
which is millions of miles from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> and racing toward a
rendezvous with the planet Mars.
   The Phobos 1 mishap follows a foul-up earlier in the week that
delayed the landing of a Soviet space capsule carrying a Soviet and
an Afghan cosmonaut.
   The unmanned Mars probe, Phobos 1, was launched <DATE>July 7</DATE>, and a
twin spacecraft, Phobos 2, on <DATE>July 12</DATE>.
   The probes were scheduled to go into orbit around Mars and in
<DATE>January</DATE> drop behind <LOCATION>Phobos</LOCATION>, the larger of the Red Planet's two
moons, to study the Martian surface, atmosphere and magnetic field.
   Sagdeyev, however, said that a ground control operator at the
<ORGANIZATION>Soviet Mission Control Center</ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION>Moscow</LOCATION> sent an incorrect command
to Phobos 1 during the night of <DATE>Aug. 29-30</DATE> that left the spacecraft
``sleeping'' and ``frozen.''
   He said the mistake was discovered <DATE>three days later</DATE> and that
ground control operators were trying to correct the problem by
sending new commands to Phobos 1. But the spacecraft was not
responding, he said.
   Sagdeyev said the probe could virtually be written off as a
total loss.
   The Soviet space research chief spoke to a reporter during an
afternoon reception at the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> ambassador's residence in honor of
<PERSON>Andrei D. Sakharov</PERSON>, the Soviet physicist and human rights activist
who is the <DATE>1975</DATE> Nobel Peace Prize laureate.
   Tass, in its report, indicated that Soviet space officials had
not had any contact with Phobos 1 for at least a week.
   ``In the two months that elapsed after the blastoff, the space
probes performed 75 radio communications sessions during which
measurings of trajectory parameters were made and operation on
onboard systems and scientific equipment was monitored,'' <ORGANIZATION>Tass</ORGANIZATION> said.
   ``On <DATE>Sept. 2</DATE>, another planned session of radio communication
with the Phobos 1 station failed to materialize,'' <ORGANIZATION>Tass</ORGANIZATION> said. ``At
that time, the station was 17 million kilometers (10.5 million
miles) from the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>. On <DATE>Sept. 9</DATE> (today), it was 19 million
kilometers (11.8 million miles) from the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>.''
   Phobos 1 was supposed to navigate with a <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> navigation system,
and a <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> official, <PERSON>Raymond J. Amorose</PERSON>, said <DATE>Thursday</DATE> the Soviets
notified the <ORGANIZATION>National Aeronautics and Space Administration</ORGANIZATION> that
they had lost contact with the craft.
   Tass indicated that scientists were in normal contact with
Phobos 2, and said <DATE>today</DATE> it was 11.8 million miles from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>.
   ``According to transmitted information, onboard systems and
instrumentation of the Phobos 2 station function smoothly,'' it
said.
   Regarding the Soviet space capsule, the state-run Soviet press
said both equipment problems and errors by the Soviet flight
commander, <PERSON>Vladimir Lyakhov</PERSON>, forced a postponement of the scheduled
<DATE>Tuesday</DATE> landing of the Soyuz TM-5 capsule. The spacecraft, also
carrying <LOCATION>Afghanistan</LOCATION>'s first man in space, <LOCATION>Ahad Abdul Mohmand</LOCATION>,
landed safely <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> on its third attempt.
</TEXT>
