<HEAD>University Developing Walking Robot for NASA</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto covering; LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM STRADER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It doesn't think like C-3PO or R2D2, but this
robot can amble along the rocky surfaces of Mars or the moon as
well as any ``Star Wars'' machine did in a galaxy far, far away.
   Scientists at <ORGANIZATION>Carnegie Mellon University</ORGANIZATION> unveiled the prototype
<DATE>Thursday</DATE>. Nicknamed the ``Ambler'' by the team that has been
working on it since <DATE>October 1987</DATE>, the aluminum robot stands 12 feet
tall and has paired stacks of three legs that enable it to traverse
uneven terrain.
   ``A walking robot was needed as an alternative to the
traditional line of wheeled rovers,'' said <PERSON>David B. Lavery</PERSON>, manager
of the <ORGANIZATION>Planetary Rovers</ORGANIZATION> program at the <ORGANIZATION>National Aeronautics and
Space Administration</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``What we want to do is demonstrate that legged vehicles ...
have an acceptable place,'' he said. ``I think the <PERSON>Ambler</PERSON> has
successfully done that.''
   <PERSON>William L. Whittaker</PERSON>, one of three <ORGANIZATION>Carnegie Mellon</ORGANIZATION> robotics
experts heading the project, said the robot moves like a
cross-country skier.
   ``A single leg reaches out in front of the others, places itself
firmly on the ground like a ski pole and then pulls the machine
forward,'' he said.
   Robots using <PERSON>Ambler</PERSON> technology are slated for use in a series of
mechanized missions to <ORGANIZATION>Mars</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Lavery</PERSON> said. He estimated walking
robots could be on the Martian surface by the end of the decade.
   President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> last week set a deadline of <DATE>2019</DATE> for Americans to
walk on Mars. The date is 50 years after <PERSON>Neil Armstrong</PERSON>, <PERSON>Michael
Collins</PERSON> and <PERSON>Buzz Aldrin</PERSON> first landed on the moon.
   The Ambler, which recently took its first steps, is one project
being evaluated by the <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> rovers program, <PERSON>Lavery</PERSON> said. The other
projects under consideration are all wheeled rovers, he said.
   ``The intent for the vehicles ... is for them to be capable of
operating on their own with just a very general set of
directions,'' he said.
   That objective has been met in the <LOCATION>Ambler</LOCATION>, according to <PERSON>Takeo
Kanade</PERSON>, <PERSON>Whittaker</PERSON>'s associate.
   ``Our goal is basically to demonstrate that actual exploration
of planets is possible,'' <PERSON>Kanade</PERSON> said.
   The <PERSON>Ambler</PERSON> has the ability to assess its environment, make
decisions, move and interact with or manipulate objects, he said.
   ``The <PERSON>Ambler</PERSON> is one of very few systems that embody all four
capabilities,'' he said.
   <PERSON>Kanade</PERSON>, who serves as co-director of <ORGANIZATION>Carnegie Mellon's Robotics
Institute</ORGANIZATION>, said the <PERSON>Ambler</PERSON> prototype will never go into space. But
the robot's technology should be ready for space flight within a
decade.
   Meantime, <PERSON>Kanade</PERSON> envisions other uses for the technology.
   ``It's not just the very narrow, kind of strange applications of
space exploration. It has a very broad impact,'' he said.
   Independent walking robots designed to adapt to a variety of
environments could be used for construction projects on the moon
and to clean up hazardous waste on <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>, he said.
   ``These machines will have to contend with rugged and soft
terrain, low temperatures, high winds, dust and equipment
failure,'' <PERSON>Kanade</PERSON> said. ``These are robots that work in
environments that are not traditionally designed for robots.
   ``The impact of this kind of program is phenomenal.''
   <PERSON>Kanade</PERSON> said the university has spent <MONEY>$4.5 million</MONEY> in <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> grants
to develop the <PERSON>Ambler</PERSON>.
</TEXT>
