<HEAD>Returning to Moon and Going to Mars Will Mean Rebuilding Space Agency</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Space, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON>, in his Apollo anniversary
speech on <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, hands <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> the job of sending Americans back to
the moon and on to Mars, <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> will first have to provide the
billions to rebuild a much-weakened space agency.
   ``Today's <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> can't do it,'' said the agency's administrator,
<ORGANIZATION>Richard Truly</ORGANIZATION>, last week.
   Since the heyday of Apollo, which put 12 Americans on the moon in
the late <DATE>1960s</DATE> and the early <DATE>1970s</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>'s work force has shrunk by
14,000 from 36,000. The managers of Apollo are retiring or have
gone; in recent months many of the top officials have resigned.
   The space agency's contractor force, which builds the
sophisticated equipment needed for such a venture, also is down from
a peak of 400,000 in the Apollo days to slightly more than 100,000
today.
   For any of the goals the president is likely to set, a space
station is a bottom line necessity and there has been considerable
opposition in <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> for spending the <MONEY>$30 billion</MONEY> that alone will
require.
   During Apollo the nation spent between <PERCENT>4 percent</PERCENT> and <PERCENT>5 percent</PERCENT> of
its federal budget on space. <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> has asked <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> for <MONEY>$13.3
billion</MONEY> next year _ about <PERCENT>1 percent</PERCENT> of the <MONEY>$1.16 trillion</MONEY> for <DATE>1990</DATE>.
   ``To do these kinds of programs, the <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> budget would have to
increase by a factor of two at the minimum, and possibly a little
higher,'' said <PERSON>Frank Martin</PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION>NASA Office of Exploration</ORGANIZATION>.
He estimated space spending would quickly climb to <MONEY>$30 billion</MONEY> a
year to land men on Mars in <DATE>2020</DATE>.
   Martin's office outlined four potential manned expeditions late
last year, two of them involving moon bases, one establishing a Mars
outpost and the other a base on the Martian moon Phobos.
   One of the moon bases would not be permanently staffed, serving
chiefly as an astronomy laboratory where telescopes _ free of
<LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s atmosphere _ could study the most distant galaxies and
search for life. The base would be serviced by visiting astronauts
every every three years.
   The second base, on the front side of the moon, would be manned
permanently.
   Many astronaut crews would be required to construct an
Antarctic-type facility, using lunar soil that is rich in metals and
silicon which could be mixed with water to form a kind of cement.
   Oxygen, which can be extracted from rocks on the moon, could be
mixed with hydrogen brought from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> to provide water and also
supply rocket fuel for Mars or other space expeditions.
   <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> has studied two approaches for exploring Mars: one using
humans, the other a robot capable of moving around the surface. A
combination of those two would place astronauts on Phobos to guide
the rover on Mars.
   ``An expedition to Phobos would establish early leadership by
sending the first human travelers to the Martian moon to explore,
conduct resource surveys and establish a science station,'' said the
exploration office in an annual report.
</TEXT>
